2026-01-30 22:49:23,235 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-6d26827a-2fc0-45f4-a416-99e8b4c7ebdf', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Always Part of the Story, Display, Horniman Museum and Gardens, London\n- Venue: Horniman Museum and Gardens\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Across the galleries at The Horniman Museum and Gardens, materials and techniques carry the argument without hype.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Listen\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Listen to labels, mounts and light, they spill the backroom decisions that shape what gets remembered at the Horniman.", "long": "<p>Across the galleries at The Horniman Museum and Gardens, materials and techniques carry the argument without hype. The rooms feel like a behind-the-scenes chat made public, where glass, paper, timber and metal do as much talking as the objects. Always Part of the Story, Display keeps circling one point, museum presentation isn’t neutral, and it never has been. Even the familiar basics, a plinth, a caption strip, a case lock, start reading as choices with consequences.</p>\\n<p>One highlight sits in the trail of archive photographs and working floor plans that track gallery layouts as they shift over time. Sightlines tighten, entrances move, object groupings change, and the mood flips with them. Nearby, a run of handwritten case labels and typed catalogue cards sits against newer interpretive text, and the tonal difference lands straight away, clipped classification next to fuller context. The display hardware comes into view too, label rails, fixings, and the scuffed edges that prove how often things get rethought.</p>\\n<p>Two don’t-miss elements keep the focus sharp without turning it into a lecture. The mounting section lays out real brackets, pins, foam forms and straps like a working kit, and it’s clear how “safe” and “seen” get negotiated object by object. Then the lighting studies, with filters, sample panels and simple side-by-side comparisons, show how glare, shadow and colour temperature steer attention, even when everything seems straightforward. A small grouping of case glass and backing boards makes the point quietly, reflection and contrast can change what reads as important.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem sits slightly off the main line of cases, a pocket of rejected label drafts with crossings-out, substituted words and awkward gaps where certainty disappears. Kept together rather than binned, they make the editing process feel tangible, what gets softened, what gets named, what stays vague. Around it, the practical stuff keeps the pressure on, worn wooden drawers from storage, handling notes, and conservation-style packing materials that hint at the labour behind a calm gallery. The politics isn’t shouted, it’s embedded in hinges, font sizes and the final wording that makes it onto the wall.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 347)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
