2026-01-30 22:49:44,864 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-3dbd40ae-7fc4-4ad4-b5fc-d190e87f7389', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: The Coming of Age, Exhibition, Wellcome Collection, London\n- Venue: Wellcome Collection\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: A sequence of rooms at The Wellcome Collection grounds the show in specific works and practical context.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Track\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Track the awkward, tender jump into adulthood through diaries, medical objects and films at Wellcome Collection in London.", "long": "<p>A sequence of rooms at The Wellcome Collection grounds the show in specific works and practical context. Set within Wellcome Collection in London, UK, The Coming of Age keeps circling the messy handover between childhood and adulthood, not as a single moment but as a chain of tests, labels and choices. One room leans hard on biology and medicine, another turns to school, family and friendship, and the tone keeps shifting between funny, uneasy and painfully familiar.</p>\\n<p>Objects do a lot of the talking. There’s a battered school exercise book filled with doodles and revision notes, close to formal material on growth charts and health advice. A case of orthodontic retainers and dental moulds sits beside changing ideas of what a “normal” body is meant to look like. Elsewhere, a prescription bottle for the oral contraceptive pill and frank pamphlets on menstruation and puberty point to how growing up gets managed through systems, not just feelings.</p>\\n<p>The highlight lands in the galleries that let real voices in. A long run of diary pages, letters and scrawled annotations pulls attention away from neat timelines and towards everyday contradictions, confidence one minute, dread the next. Don’t miss the listening station of recorded memories (awkward firsts, family rules, sudden independence), it’s quietly gripping. Another don’t-miss sits in the projection space, where sex education films and public information clips play on a loop, all stiff language and careful reassurance, sometimes undercut by what people recall actually learning.</p>\\n<p>Along the way, wall texts keep tying private experience to bigger forces, schooling, the law, diagnosis, and the NHS. The hidden gem is a small vitrine of acne treatments and beauty adverts, their promises of control and “clear skin” doing more cultural work than they admit. Photographs of youth groups, uniforms and bedrooms keep returning as evidence, not decoration, and the last room leaves a scatter of competing definitions of adulthood sitting side by side.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 318)\n- copy mentions visit duration/time-to-spend (remove duration from short/long)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
