2026-01-30 22:50:08,299 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-dc677dc7-c168-469c-8408-ed1b7daf83b2', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: The Coming of Age, Exhibition, Wellcome Collection, London\n- Venue: Wellcome Collection\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: A sequence of rooms at The Wellcome Collection grounds the show in specific works and practical context.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Track\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Track the awkward, tender jump into adulthood through diaries, medical objects and films at Wellcome Collection in London.", "long": "<p>A sequence of rooms at The Wellcome Collection grounds the show in specific works and practical context. At Wellcome Collection in London, UK, The Coming of Age keeps circling the messy handover between childhood and adulthood, not as a single moment but as a chain of tests, labels and choices. One room leans on biology and medicine, another turns to school, family and friendship, and the tone shifts between funny, uneasy and painfully familiar.</p>\\n<p>Objects do a lot of the talking. There’s a battered school exercise book packed with doodles, revision notes and a few crossed out ambitions, set near material on growth charts and health advice. Orthodontic retainers and dental moulds sit alongside diagrams that sort bodies into stages, and the effect is more blunt than nostalgic. Elsewhere, packaging for the oral contraceptive pill and straightforward pamphlets on menstruation and puberty point to how growing up gets managed through systems, not just feelings. A cluster of exam papers and report comments brings in pressure that doesn’t need any decoration.</p>\\n<p>The highlight lands where real voices cut through the official language. A run of diary pages, letters and scrawled annotations pulls attention away from neat categories and towards everyday contradictions, confidence one minute, dread the next. Don’t miss the listening station of recorded memories, awkward firsts, family rules, sudden independence, it stays with the mind because it sounds ordinary. Don’t miss the projection space either, where sex education films and public information clips loop through careful reassurance and stiff euphemisms, sometimes undercut by what people remember actually learning. The show keeps nudging between private experience and public policy without forcing a single moral.</p>\\n<p>Along the way, wall texts tie adolescence to schooling, the law, diagnosis, and the NHS, with an eye on who gets judged, who gets helped, and who gets ignored. The hidden gem is a small vitrine of acne treatments and beauty adverts, their promises of control and “clear skin” doing cultural work that’s easy to overlook. Photographs of youth groups, uniforms and bedrooms keep returning as evidence rather than decoration, and a final cluster of definitions of adulthood sits side by side, sometimes conflicting, sometimes oddly compatible.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- copy mentions visit duration/time-to-spend (remove duration from short/long)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
