2026-01-30 22:50:28,307 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-2f7f4719-1dad-4c23-bbff-bcd81a2494c3', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Always Part of the Story, Display, Horniman Museum and Gardens, London\n- Venue: Horniman Museum and Gardens\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Across the galleries at The Horniman Museum and Gardens, materials and techniques carry the argument without hype.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Listen\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Listen to labels, mounts and light, they spill the backroom decisions that shape what gets remembered at the Horniman.", "long": "<p>Across the galleries at The Horniman Museum and Gardens, materials and techniques carry the argument without hype. The spaces read like working notes made public, where glass, paper, timber and metal do as much talking as the objects. Always Part of the Story, Display keeps circling one simple point, museum display isn’t neutral, and it never has been. Even the basics, a plinth, a caption strip, a case lock, start to feel like decisions with consequences. Scuffed edges, old screw holes and tape shadows on supports quietly admit how often plans get rethought.</p>\\n<p>One highlight sits in the trail of archive photographs and marked-up floor plans that track gallery layouts as they shift. Sightlines tighten, entrances move, and object groupings get re-argued, sometimes for practical reasons, sometimes for tone. Close by, handwritten case labels and typed catalogue cards face newer interpretive text, and the difference lands fast, clipped classification next to fuller context. There’s real display hardware on view too, including a worn mahogany label rail, a steel case hinge with paint build-up, and a Perspex mount that shows its stress points.</p>\\n<p>Two don’t-miss elements keep things grounded in everyday practice. First, the mounting section lays out brackets, pins, foam cradles and straps like a working kit, making it obvious how “safe” and “seen” get negotiated object by object. Then the lighting studies, with gel filters, sample panels and straightforward side-by-side comparisons, show how glare, shadow and colour temperature steer attention even when everything looks calm. A small run of case glass and backing boards underlines the point, reflection and contrast can decide what reads as important.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem sits slightly off the main line of cases, a pocket of rejected label drafts with crossings-out, swapped nouns and blank spaces where certainty drops away. Kept together rather than binned, they make the editing process tangible, what gets softened, what gets named, what stays vague. Around it, the practical stuff keeps pressing in, storage drawers with rubbed handles, conservation packing materials, and plain instructions that prioritise stability over drama. Tiny shifts in font size, line breaks and label placement keep proving how authority can hide in layout.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
