2026-01-30 22:51:38,381 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-1cffc9bc-9f11-4e33-8110-8bfcd222a958', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Tracey Emin\n- Venue: Tate Modern\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Across the galleries at The Tate Modern, materials and techniques carry the argument without hype.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Compare\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Compare raw drawings, neon phrases and sewn blankets, plus an unmade bed, as Tate Modern keeps confession sharp and unsentimental.", "long": "<p>Across the galleries at The Tate Modern, materials and techniques carry the argument without hype. Tracey Emin’s work moves between confession and control, with quick lines, blunt wording and a stubborn sense of the body in space. In London, UK, the rooms keep switching tempo: a hushed cluster of drawings, then a hit of neon, then fabric that reads like a diary page pinned to a wall.</p>\\n<p>The highlight lands with a jolt: <i>My Bed</i>. The unmade mattress, stained sheets and surrounding debris sit under museum lights without softening the point. It’s intimate, awkward and stubbornly ordinary, and it makes the rest of the show feel less like art history and more like aftermath. The work’s stillness also throws attention onto what’s usually edited out, tiredness, shame, desire, the mess that stays.</p>\\n<p>Two don’t-miss elements sit at opposite ends of the emotional scale. One is the run of neon text works, including <i>More Passion</i> and <i>I Want My Time With You</i>, where the handwriting style turns longing into a public sign. The other is the works on paper: fast drawings and monoprints that keep the hand visible, smudges included. Faces appear and vanish, bodies are hinted at with a few stubborn marks, and the tone stays direct rather than lyrical.</p>\\n<p>Elsewhere, sewn blankets and appliqu\\u0000e9 pieces pull domestic craft into sharper territory, with stitched phrases that don’t try to behave. Paintings push colour hard, then leave it to sag and scrape, as if the surface can’t hold the feeling for long. A small bronze figure shifts the mood again, carrying the same autobiographical charge into weight and balance.</p>\\n<p>The hidden gem is a quieter pocket of early, tightly packed works on paper set slightly apart from the louder rooms. In that corner, the language is less quotable and more private, and the marks look made in a hurry, then kept anyway. It’s the kind of section that reframes the bigger statements as a chain of smaller, repeated decisions, line after line.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 333)\n- long uses banned word \'you\'\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
