2026-01-30 22:51:48,276 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-bba82b9c-0cb1-48f5-b4d5-c2a48c2213e5', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Wes Anderson\n- Venue: Design Museum\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Inside the galleries at The Design Museum, the route moves from key works to supporting material and context.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Read\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Read how Anderson’s worlds get built, with puppets, miniatures, scripts and costumes from films like The Grand Budapest Hotel, now at London’s Design Museum.", "long": "<p>Inside the galleries at The Design Museum, the route moves from key works to supporting material and context. The mood is precise and playful, with a strong focus on how Wes Anderson’s films get made, not just how they look on screen. In London, the displays keep circling back to craft, typography, and the small decisions that lock in tone.</p>\\n<p>The highlight is a Grand Budapest Hotel model, shown with production notes that spell out sightlines, colour choices, and camera angles. Nearby, storyboards and overhead diagrams make the symmetry feel engineered rather than accidental. There’s also artwork and layout material that tracks recurring motifs, from regimented luggage labels to deadpan signage.</p>\\n<p>Two don’t-miss elements sit at opposite ends of the process. First, stop-motion characters from Fantastic Mr. Fox and Isle of Dogs, complete with armatures, paint wear, and replacement faces that explain how a tiny expression lands on film. Second, working scripts and call sheets covered in annotations, where jokes, pauses, and scene rhythm get tuned line by line. Production designer Adam Stockhausen’s drawings add another layer, with set plans that read like architectural briefs.</p>\\n<p>Costume material brings texture and character. A purple concierge jacket tied to Gustave H sits alongside details about fabrics and fittings, and Margot Tenenbaum’s fur coat and tennis dress are treated as design objects, not just wardrobe. Prop pieces lean into the same thinking, including The Royal Tenenbaums family ephemera and Moonrise Kingdom paperwork that turns invented bureaucracy into something believable.</p>\\n<p>The hidden gem is a cluster of small, easily missed items, typography tests, label mock-ups, and continuity Polaroids, pinned up as if they’ve just come off a studio wall. They quietly underline how much of Anderson’s style lives in paper cuts and print choices, and a stack of annotated contact sheets sits nearby.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 299)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
