2026-01-30 22:52:16,788 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-a69afcfb-2973-4421-8bba-adbcb5a2a025', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Wes Anderson\n- Venue: Design Museum\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Inside the galleries at The Design Museum, the route moves from key works to supporting material and context.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Read\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Read how scripts, puppets and meticulous models shape deadpan film worlds at the Design Museum in London.", "long": "<p>Inside the galleries at The Design Museum, the route moves from key works to supporting material and context. The tone stays practical, focusing on decisions and labour rather than screen myth. In London, the story keeps circling craft, typography, and the tiny adjustments that make a frame feel perfectly controlled.</p>\\n<p>The highlight is a detailed model from <i>The Grand Budapest Hotel</i>, paired with production notes that pin down sightlines, paint mixes, and camera movement. Nearby, storyboards and overhead set diagrams make the famous symmetry feel engineered, not accidental. There’s also a run of prop graphics, luggage labels, hotel stationery, and deadpan signage, where wording and letter spacing carry as much character as a costume.</p>\\n<p>Two don’t-miss elements sit at opposite ends of the process. First, stop-motion puppets from <i>Fantastic Mr. Fox</i> and <i>Isle of Dogs</i> sit under close lighting that makes armatures, fur wear, and replacement faces easy to read. The scuffs and repairs matter, because they show how animation is held together shot by shot. Second, working scripts, call sheets, and annotated scene pages lay out timing and rhythm in plain ink, with cuts, arrows, and rewritten lines that turn jokes into beats.</p>\\n<p>Design work carries real weight here. Production designer Adam Stockhausen’s drawings and set plans read like architectural documents, complete with measurements and materials. Costume pieces land as design objects too, including a purple concierge jacket tied to Gustave H and Margot Tenenbaum’s fur coat and tennis dress from <i>The Royal Tenenbaums</i>. A section of <i>Moonrise Kingdom</i> paperwork leans into invented bureaucracy, with forms and stamps that still feel oddly believable.</p>\\n<p>The hidden gem is a cluster of small paper items pinned up as if they’ve just come off a studio wall, typography tests, label mock-ups, continuity Polaroids, and scraps of ephemera. It’s easy to drift past them, yet they quietly underline how much of the style lives in print choices and handling. A stack of annotated contact sheets sits alongside colour swatches and prop menus.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 331)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
