gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Read\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Read how models, puppets and printed ephemera drive a dryly precise film world at the Design Museum in London.", "long": "<p>Inside the galleries at The Design Museum, the route moves from key works to supporting material and context. The tone stays practical, sticking to decisions and labour rather than screen myth. In London, the story keeps circling craft, typography, and the tiny adjustments that make a frame feel tightly controlled.</p>\\n<p>The highlight is a detailed model from <i>The Grand Budapest Hotel</i>, set alongside production notes that pin down sightlines, paint mixes, and camera movement. Nearby, storyboards and overhead set diagrams make the famous symmetry feel engineered, not accidental. A run of prop graphics, luggage labels, hotel stationery, and deadpan signage lands with real weight, because wording and letter spacing carry as much character as a costume.</p>\\n<p>Two don’t-miss elements sit at opposite ends of the process. First, stop-motion puppets from <i>Fantastic Mr. Fox</i> and <i>Isle of Dogs</i> sit under close lighting that makes armatures, fur wear, and replacement faces clear. Scuffs, repairs, and finger marks matter here, showing how animation holds together shot by shot. Second, working scripts, call sheets, and annotated scene pages map timing and rhythm in plain ink, with cuts, arrows, and rewritten lines that turn jokes into beats.</p>\\n<p>Design work carries the argument. Production designer Adam Stockhausen’s drawings and set plans read like architectural documents, complete with measurements, materials, and notes on finish. Costume pieces land as design objects too, including a purple concierge jacket tied to Gustave H and Margot Tenenbaum’s fur coat and tennis dress from <i>The Royal Tenenbaums</i>. A section of <i>Moonrise Kingdom</i> paperwork leans into invented bureaucracy, with forms, stamps, and badges that still feel oddly believable.</p>\\n<p>The hidden gem is a cluster of small paper items pinned up as if they’ve just come off a studio wall, typography tests, label mock-ups, continuity Polaroids, and scraps of ephemera. They sit close to colour swatches, prop menus, and annotated contact sheets, where tiny shifts in hue and texture show up as hard choices. Display cases keep the scale intimate, so the grain of paper, tape edges, and worn corners stay visible.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 340)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
