2026-01-30 22:52:42,799 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-f9eb7d12-4ab3-49a5-ba2d-c5de1ffda9e5', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Tracey Emin\n- Venue: Tate Modern\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Across the galleries at The Tate Modern, materials and techniques carry the argument without hype.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Compare\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Compare neon confessions, fast drawings and stitched blankets, with My Bed as the gut-punch centrepiece at Tate Modern in London.", "long": "<p>Across the galleries at The Tate Modern, materials and techniques carry the argument without hype. Tracey Emin’s work moves between confession and control, with quick lines, blunt wording and a stubborn sense of the body in space. In London, the rooms keep switching tempo, a hush of drawings, then a hit of neon, then fabric that reads like a diary page pinned to a wall. Video, sculpture and text sit side by side, and the hang keeps the hand behind the work in plain view.</p>\\n<p>The highlight lands with a jolt: <i>My Bed</i>. The unmade mattress, stained sheets and surrounding debris sit under museum lights without softening the point. It’s intimate, awkward and stubbornly ordinary, and it makes the rest of the show feel less like art history and more like aftermath. That stillness sharpens attention on what’s usually edited out, tiredness, shame, desire, the mess that stays.</p>\\n<p>Two don’t-miss elements sit at opposite ends of the emotional scale. One is the run of neon text works, including <i>More Passion</i>, where the cursive glow turns longing into a public sign and the spelling stays personal. The other is the film <i>Why I Never Became a Dancer</i>, which holds the room with voice, memory and a refusal to tidy up the story. The soundtrack drifts into nearby spaces and changes how the quieter works read.</p>\\n<p>Works on paper keep the hand visible, smudges included. Fast drawings and monoprints let faces appear and vanish, bodies hinted at with a few stubborn marks, and the tone stays direct rather than lyrical. Elsewhere, sewn blankets and appliqué pieces pull domestic craft into sharper territory, with stitched phrases that don’t try to behave. <i>Exorcism of the Last Painting I Ever Made</i> brings paint, walls and process into the open, turning the act of making into evidence, with traces of decisions left on show.</p>\\n<p>The hidden gem is a quieter pocket of early, tightly packed works on paper set slightly apart from the louder rooms. In that corner the language is less quotable and more private, and the marks look made in a hurry, then kept anyway. Small shifts in paper tone and pressure start to matter, and a couple of modest framed sheets hold their ground next to the bigger statements, as if the story’s still being worked out.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
