2026-01-30 22:54:17,348 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-54e8c1b8-800b-434d-bf03-8d3eed85568c', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Painting the French Riviera, Exhibition, Royal Academy of Arts, London\n- Venue: Royal Academy of Arts\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Galleries at The Royal Academy of Arts set out a clear route through materials, techniques and context.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Unpick\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Unpick Riviera colour habits and seaside motifs, tracing quick studies, bold oils and prints through the Royal Academy of Arts in London.", "long": "<p>Galleries at The Royal Academy of Arts set out a clear route through materials, techniques and context. Painting the French Riviera is up and running in London, all hard light, salt air and that tricky, glittering sea. Oils, watercolours and prints sit close together, so changes in surface and speed register straight away.</p>\\n<p>The hang keeps coming back to practical questions: how glare shifts colour, why shadows turn violet on a white wall, and what happens to a horizon line when the water won’t sit still. Plenty of works start as on-the-spot studies, then tighten into studio paintings, with corrections, scraped-back passages and reworked skies left visible rather than tidied away.</p>\\n<p>A highlight comes with the move from open coast to sheltered corners, hotel terraces, courtyards and gardens, where pattern and architecture take over from panorama. Henri Matisse’s Nice years are used as a touchstone for interiors that trap southern light, while Pierre Bonnard’s Le Cannet links show how a domestic view can still carry the heat outside. A thread on Pablo Picasso around Vallauris and the coastline adds bite, with forms simplified until the scene reads in blocks of sun and shade.</p>\\n<p>Two don’t-miss elements land well. First, a room of harbour and promenade images, masts, parasols, striped awnings and fast shadows, where brushwork stays brisk and decisions feel immediate. Second, the section on colour economy, where limited palettes still hold midday intensity, and wall texts point out which pigments keep their punch under high light.</p>\\n<p>The hidden gem sits slightly off the main flow: a quieter pocket of works on paper. Pencil scaffolding, wash tests, and small compositional grids reveal how much planning sits under a breezy shoreline view, and the marginal notes feel like overheard studio talk.</p>\\n<p>There are also a few grounded, workaday objects, paint boxes, palette knives and dog-eared sketchbooks, that make the whole enterprise feel less like myth-making and more like problem-solving under a bright sky.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 322)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
