2026-01-30 22:54:41,161 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-4d94b200-b742-4e80-9e03-a936f7866b04', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Winifred Gill\n- Venue: The Courtauld Gallery\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Labels at The Courtauld Gallery keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Map\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Map a London working life through drawings, letters and studio odds and ends at The Courtauld Gallery, with two don’t-miss stops and a tucked-away gem.", "long": "<p>Labels at The Courtauld Gallery keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft. In London, Winifred Gill comes across as someone who works things out on paper, then carries that thinking into tools, scraps, and practical routines. The display stays close to the grain of everyday making, so smudged graphite, rubbed corners, and patched seams matter as much as finished results. It feels like a life rebuilt from what survives, not from grand claims.</p>\\n<p>The highlight is a tight group of drawings, quick pencil studies on thin sheets that still hold the speed of the hand. Lines dart, pause, and restart, and there are plenty of corrections that show decision-making in real time. Some sheets keep their working marks, with pinholes and faint guidelines still visible. Nearby, a worn paint box and a small bundle of brushes keep the focus on labour, with stained handles and dried pigment doing most of the talking.</p>\\n<p>Two don’t-miss moments sit in the quieter corners. One is a pocket diary opened to packed entries, with crossings-out, squeezed-in notes, and reminders that turn planning into a kind of sketching. The other is a run of letters, folded and refolded, where Gill’s voice stays practical, sometimes warm, sometimes brisk, especially when money, space, or deadlines press in. The paper itself carries a lot, from creases to blunt pencil underlining.</p>\\n<p>There’s also a small oil sketch on board, still visibly worked, with underpainting showing through and thumb-sized adjustments held in place rather than smoothed away. Photographs and newspaper cuttings add context without drowning the room in backstory, and a scattering of exhibition catalogues, ticket stubs, and a signed bookplate hint at networks and habits. It’s the kind of material that makes reputation feel secondary to the day-to-day grind of keeping going.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem sits almost in plain sight: a hand-stitched sampler with initials and even thread, easy to miss until the light catches the texture. It quietly links the drawing hand to other kinds of skill, including careful mending and patient repetition, and it sits comfortably alongside paper repairs, tidy mounts, and the small acts of keeping things in use.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
