2026-01-30 22:54:56,607 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-6ae5610b-b51a-4f8b-90fb-919d5f370dc3', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Painting the French Riviera, Exhibition, Royal Academy of Arts, London\n- Venue: Royal Academy of Arts\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Galleries at The Royal Academy of Arts set out a clear route through materials, techniques and context.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Unpick\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Unpick Riviera colour habits and seaside motifs, tracing quick studies, bold oils and prints at the Royal Academy of Arts.", "long": "<p>Galleries at The Royal Academy of Arts set out a clear route through materials, techniques and context. Painting the French Riviera is up and running, all hard light, salt air and that tricky, glittering sea. Oils, watercolours and prints sit close together, so shifts in surface and speed register straight away. The wall texts stay practical, keeping an eye on what the weather does to colour and how artists respond when everything turns too bright to trust.</p>\\n<p>The hang keeps coming back to questions painters actually wrestle with: how glare flattens a view, why shadows turn violet on a white wall, and what happens to a horizon line when the water won’t sit still. Plenty of works start as on-the-spot studies, then tighten into studio paintings, with corrections, scraped-back passages and reworked skies left visible rather than tidied away. There’s a steady rhythm between quick notations and slower, more structured compositions.</p>\\n<p>A highlight lands with the move from open coast to sheltered corners, hotel terraces, courtyards and gardens, where pattern and architecture take over from panorama. Henri Matisse’s Nice years act as a touchstone for interiors that trap southern light on tiled floors and pale walls. Pierre Bonnard at Le Cannet shifts the heat into domestic space, pushing colour until a room seems to glow from within. A thread on Pablo Picasso around Vallauris adds bite, with forms pared down until the scene reads in blocks of sun and shade.</p>\\n<p>Two don’t-miss elements come through clearly. First, a room of harbour and promenade images, masts, parasols, striped awnings and fast shadows, where brushwork stays brisk and decisions feel immediate. Second, the section on colour economy, where limited palettes still hold midday intensity, and labels call out the work of choosing a handful of pigments that don’t turn to mud under strong light.</p>\\n<p>The hidden gem sits slightly off the main flow, a quieter pocket of works on paper. Pencil scaffolding, wash tests, small compositional grids and margin notes give away the planning under a breezy shoreline view, and the paper itself carries the story, buckled edges, rubbed highlights, and thumbprints caught in dried pigment.</p>\\n<p>A few grounded studio bits sit nearby, paint boxes, palette knives and dog-eared sketchbooks, plus small maps and photographs that pin specific bays and towns to the images on the walls.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
