2026-01-30 22:55:33,062 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-c93cd8ab-2cf7-4874-8c5a-6dd33d7479a9', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Winifred Gill\n- Venue: The Courtauld Gallery\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Labels at The Courtauld Gallery keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Map\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Map a working life in pencil studies, letters and a pocket diary at The Courtauld Gallery, plus a stitched sampler hiding in plain sight.", "long": "<p>Labels at The Courtauld Gallery keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft. In London, UK, the room sets out a practical, grounded account of Winifred Gill, built from paper, tools, and the small traces work leaves behind. Nothing leans on grand statements. Instead, rubbed corners, pinholes, and repaired edges carry the story, and the choices feel deliberate, letting materials speak in their own register.</p>\\n<p>The highlight is a tight cluster of pencil studies on thin sheets, still full of starts, stops, and revisions. Lines dart and then hesitate, with erased passages and fresh marks laid over the top. Some pages keep faint guidelines and smudged fingerprints, so the thinking stays visible rather than polished away. A small oil sketch on board nearby keeps that same directness, with underpainting peeking through and quick adjustments left intact.</p>\\n<p>Two don’t-miss elements sit slightly apart from the drawings, but they sharpen the picture. One is a pocket diary opened to dense entries, crossings-out, and squeezed-in reminders that read like sketching in words. The other is a run of letters, folded and refolded, where tone shifts between warm, brisk, and strictly practical, especially when money, space, and deadlines press. Creases, ink blots, and pencil underlining do as much work as the sentences.</p>\\n<p>Tools keep the focus on labour rather than legend. A worn paint box and a small bundle of brushes sit with stained handles and dried pigment, the kind of kit that gets used, wiped, and used again. Photographs and newspaper cuttings add context without drowning the wall in biography. A scattering of exhibition catalogues, ticket stubs, and a signed bookplate hints at networks, habits, and the unglamorous logistics of keeping a practice moving.</p>\\n<p>The hidden gem is a hand-stitched sampler with initials worked in even thread, easy to pass by until the light catches the texture. It quietly links the drawing hand to other kinds of skill, including careful mending and patient repetition, and it sits comfortably beside paper repairs, tidy mounts, and the small acts of keeping things in use.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 343)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
