2026-01-30 22:56:21,487 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-72097f05-5089-4efa-a6f5-be3b3fa40693', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Our Story with David Attenborough, Exhibition, Natural History Museum, London\n- Venue: Natural History Museum\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Across the galleries at The Natural History Museum, materials and techniques carry the argument without hype.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Study\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Study Earth’s deep-time turning points as David Attenborough narrates an immersive film at the Natural History Museum in London.", "long": "<p>Across the galleries at The Natural History Museum, materials and techniques carry the argument without hype. The room stays dark and calm, then light and sound do the heavy lifting. David Attenborough’s narration keeps things plain-spoken, the same steady tone familiar from Planet Earth, Blue Planet II and A Life on Our Planet, but here it’s pinned to a single, continuous thread about how life changes, survives and sometimes vanishes.</p>\\n<p>At the centre is a large-scale, wraparound projection with crisp animation and real-world imagery stitched together into one flowing sequence. It moves from early oceans and the first simple life through bursts of diversity, mass extinctions and rapid adaptation, then lands firmly in the present. The highlight is the way the visuals shift scale without fuss, from microscopic processes to whole-planet systems, so evolution feels like a set of pressures and responses rather than a parade of creatures.</p>\\n<p>Don’t miss the opening stretch, which compresses deep time into a few sharp, legible ideas, with tectonic motion and changing atmospheres made easy to follow. Don’t miss the mid-section on extinction and recovery, where the soundtrack drops back and the images slow down, letting cause and effect sit in the mind. It’s not sentimental, just direct, with a clear line between past upheavals and today’s accelerating change.</p>\\n<p>The exhibition keeps the language grounded and avoids finger-pointing, even when it turns to human influence, land use and warming seas. London’s Natural History Museum setting adds its own quiet weight, because the story sits alongside one of the world’s great scientific collections, even when the focus stays on moving image rather than cases and labels.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem is a small side section that unpacks the science behind the sequences with short text, diagrams and definitions, handy for anyone wanting the key terms without a textbook tone. It’s also a nice breather between the big scenes and the final run of images, where the narration turns from what happened to what’s happening now.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 329)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
