2026-01-30 22:56:36,706 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-fa33f7d3-6259-4d91-844c-2c4d40dee59c', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Hepworth and Nicholson\n- Venue: The Courtauld Gallery\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Labels at The Courtauld Gallery keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Trace\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Trace two St Ives modernists through carvings, reliefs and letters at The Courtauld Gallery in London.", "long": "<p>Labels at The Courtauld Gallery keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft. The rooms bring Barbara Hepworth and Ben Nicholson into close conversation, not as tidy legends but as working artists swapping ideas, materials, and sharp edits. It’s a show that stays hands-on, with surfaces, joins, pencil lines and tool marks doing as much talking as any wall text.</p>\\n<p>Hepworth’s sculpture anchors the mood, with carved wood and stone forms that press negative space into the middle of things. Even at a small scale, the tension between smooth planes and cut edges feels deliberate, like decisions taken in real time. Nicholson answers with paintings, drawings, and his white reliefs, where shallow depth, scored geometry and painted shadow turn restraint into structure. Together, the work keeps returning to the same question, how far form can be simplified without losing the pull of the natural world.</p>\\n<p>A highlight sits in the tight pairing of a pierced Hepworth carving with a nearby Nicholson relief, where one object’s hollow becomes the other’s line. Two don’t-miss elements stand out. First, the run of Nicholson reliefs and still lifes, pared back to blocks, circles and cool tonal shifts, rewards a slow look at edges and paint handling. Second, Hepworth’s studies and maquettes show the route from drawing to volume, with measurements, corrections and reworked contours that make the finished pieces feel less inevitable.</p>\\n<p>The exhibition also keeps its social world in view, with documentary photographs and printed matter that pin the work to everyday routines, studio floors, and arguments about modernism. A hidden gem appears in the smaller materials, a modest case of letters, sketchbook pages, and working tools that makes the partnership feel practical rather than romantic. In London, UK, The Courtauld’s calm galleries suit the show’s quiet insistence on looking closely, right down to a rasp’s scrape and a graphite smudge left uncleaned</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 314)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
