2026-01-30 22:56:57,350 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-6f98bca8-641c-4a2f-9573-c143380bcf9d', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Hepworth and Nicholson\n- Venue: The Courtauld Gallery\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Labels at The Courtauld Gallery keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Trace\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Trace two St Ives modernists as carvings and reliefs trade ideas across The Courtauld Gallery in London.", "long": "<p>Labels at The Courtauld Gallery keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft. The rooms set Barbara Hepworth and Ben Nicholson side by side, not as tidy legends but as working artists testing materials, stealing good solutions, and throwing out what doesn’t hold up. It’s grounded in touch, with surfaces, joins, pencil pressure and tool marks doing as much talking as any wall text.</p>\\n<p>Hepworth’s sculpture drives the mood, with carved wood and stone forms that push negative space into the centre of things. Strings and pierced openings sharpen the sense of tension, like breath held inside a solid. Nicholson answers with paintings, drawings, and his white reliefs, where shallow depth, scored geometry and paint-thin shifts of tone make restraint feel active. The conversation keeps circling one question, how far form can be pared back without losing the pull of landscape, light, and the body.</p>\\n<p>A highlight comes in a tight pairing of a pierced Hepworth carving with a nearby Nicholson relief, where one object’s hollow becomes the other’s line, and the eye flicks between depth and flatness. Two don’t-miss elements stand out. First, the run of Nicholson reliefs and still lifes rewards close looking at edges, tiny shadows, and the way a scraped line can lock a whole composition. Second, Hepworth’s studies and small maquettes show the route from drawing to volume, complete with measurements, revisions, and contours reworked until they read clean.</p>\\n<p>It also keeps the social world in view through documentary photographs, printed matter, and studio ephemera that pin the work to everyday routines and arguments about modern art. A hidden gem sits in the quieter material, a modest group of letters, sketchbook pages, and working tools that makes the partnership feel practical rather than romantic. In London, UK, the galleries suit the show’s insistence on close looking, right down to a rasp’s scrape and a graphite smudge left uncleaned, with small decisions sitting in plain sight</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 324)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
