ts, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Trace\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Trace two St Ives modernists as carving, paint, and paper trade ideas across The Courtauld Gallery in London.", "long": "<p>Labels at The Courtauld Gallery keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft. The rooms put Barbara Hepworth and Ben Nicholson in steady conversation, not as tidy legends but as working artists trying things out, nicking good solutions, and dropping whatever doesn’t hold. It’s hands-on modernism, with tool marks, pencil pressure and paint skins carrying the argument as much as the captions do.</p>\\n<p>Hepworth sets the pace with sculpture that treats air like a material. Pierced forms and stringed passages tighten the geometry, while wood grain and stone edges stay present rather than polished away. Nicholson answers with paintings and his white reliefs, where shallow depth, scored lines and small shifts of tone make restraint feel active. Together, the work keeps circling the same problem, how far form can be pared back and still hang on to landscape, light, and the body.</p>\\n<p>A highlight lands in a close pairing of a pierced Hepworth carving with a nearby Nicholson relief, where a hollowed space snaps into a drawn line and the eye keeps toggling between depth and flatness. Two don’t-miss elements stand out. First, the sequence of Nicholson reliefs and still lifes rewards slow attention to edges, tiny shadows and the way a scraped groove locks a whole composition into place. Second, Hepworth’s drawings and plaster maquettes lay out the route from sketch to volume, with measurements, revisions and contours reworked until they read clean and inevitable.</p>\\n<p>The social world stays in view through documentary photographs, printed matter and studio ephemera that tie the work to everyday routines and real disagreements about what modern art is for. A hidden gem sits in the quieter material, a small group of letters, sketchbook pages and carving tools (rasps, chisels, lengths of string) that makes the partnership feel practical rather than romantic. In London, UK, the galleries suit the show’s insistence on close looking, with smudged graphite, rubbed paint and the stubborn grain of wood left to do their part</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 330)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
