2026-01-30 22:57:34,620 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-2c3ba64e-9ae0-4034-96ab-7c23fc31a3d5', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Hepworth and Nicholson\n- Venue: The Courtauld Gallery\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Labels at The Courtauld Gallery keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Trace\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Trace Hepworth and Nicholson trading ideas in carving, relief and paper, with tools, photos and maquettes keeping things grounded.", "long": "<p>Labels at The Courtauld Gallery keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft. The rooms set Barbara Hepworth and Ben Nicholson in steady conversation, not as tidy legends but as working artists trying things out, borrowing solutions, and dropping whatever doesn’t hold. It’s modernism with fingerprints, where tool marks, pencil pressure and paint skins carry the argument as much as the captions do.</p>\\n<p>Hepworth sets the pace with sculpture that treats air like a material. Pierced forms pull the eye through voids, while stringed passages tighten the geometry and make tension visible. Wood grain and stone edges stay present rather than smoothed away, so the making never disappears. Nicholson answers with paintings, still lifes and his white reliefs, where shallow depth, scored lines and small shifts of tone keep restraint active. Together the work keeps circling the same problem, how far form can be pared back and still hang on to landscape, light and the body.</p>\\n<p>A highlight lands in a close pairing of a pierced Hepworth carving with a nearby Nicholson relief, where a hollowed space snaps into a drawn line and the eye keeps switching between depth and flatness. Two don’t-miss elements stand out. First, the run of Nicholson reliefs rewards close attention to edges, tiny shadows and the way a scraped groove locks a whole composition into place. Second, Hepworth’s drawings and plaster maquettes lay out the route from sketch to volume, with measurements, revisions and contours reworked until they read clean and decided.</p>\\n<p>The social world stays in view through documentary photographs, printed matter and studio ephemera that tie the work to everyday routines and real disagreements about what modern art is for. A hidden gem sits in the quieter material, a small cluster of letters, sketchbook pages and carving tools (rasps, chisels, lengths of string) that makes the partnership feel practical rather than romantic. In London, UK, the display suits the show’s insistence on close looking, with smudged graphite, rubbed paint and stubborn grain left to do their part.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 338)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
