2026-01-30 22:57:59,721 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-398ab60d-4c0c-40cf-983c-6d429776b47c', 'json_data': {'input': "Translate the following Divento temporary exhibition content.\n\nRules (follow exactly):\n- Return ONLY a JSON object matching the provided schema.\n- Do not add citations, links, or URLs.\n- Avoid em/en dash characters (— or –); rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Keep all HTML tags intact in 'long' and return valid HTML.\n- Do NOT add extra blank lines/newlines.\n- For 'short': maximum 164 characters in the target language, keep natural phrasing.\n- For 'name': translate only what should be translated; keep proper nouns/titles as appropriate.\n- For zh-CN: translate ALL prose into Simplified Chinese; Latin script is allowed ONLY for proper nouns and official artwork/series titles.\n\nEnglish inputs:\n- name_en: Hepworth and Nicholson, Exhibition, The Courtauld Gallery, London: 6 June-4 October 2026\n- short_en: Trace the push and pull between two British modernists, from pierced sculpture to white reliefs, with tools and paper trails in the mix.\nlong_en_html:\n<p>Labels at The Courtauld Gallery keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft. The rooms set Barbara Hepworth and Ben Nicholson in steady conversation, not as tidy legends but as working artists trying things out, borrowing solutions, and dropping whatever doesn’t hold. It’s modernism with fingerprints, where tool marks, pencil pressure and paint skins carry the argument as much as the captions do. There’s plenty of paper in the mix too, from quick studies to careful diagrams that pin down proportions and spacing.</p><p>Hepworth sets the pace with sculpture that treats air like a material. Pierced forms pull the eye through voids, while stringed passages tighten the geometry and make tension visible. Wood grain and stone edges stay present rather than smoothed away, so the making never disappears. Nicholson answers with paintings, still lifes and his white reliefs, where shallow depth, scored lines and small shifts of tone keep restraint active. Some of Nicholson’s still lifes hold everyday objects, a jug, a glass, a guitar, reduced to clean angles that still feel domestic. Together the work keeps circling the same problem, how far form can be pared back and still hang on to landscape, light and the body.</p><p>A highlight lands in a close pairing of a pierced Hepworth carving with a nearby Nicholson relief, where a hollowed space snaps into a drawn line and the eye keeps switching between depth and flatness. Two don’t-miss elements stand out. First, the run of Nicholson reliefs rewards close attention to edges, tiny shadows and the way a scraped groove locks a whole composition into place. Second, Hepworth’s drawings and plaster maquettes lay out the route from sketch to volume, with measurements, revisions and contours reworked until they read clean and decided.</p><p>The social world stays in view through documentary photographs, printed matter and studio ephemera that tie the work to everyday routines and real disagreements about what modern art is for. A hidden gem sits in the quieter material, a small cluster of letters, sketchbook pages and carving tools (rasps, chisels, lengths of string) that makes the partnership feel practical rather than romantic. In London, UK, the display suits the show’s insistence on close looking, with smudged graphite, rubbed paint and stubborn grain left to do their part.</p>\n", 'max_output_tokens': 9000, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_translation_bundle', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'fr': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}, 'es': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}, 'it': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}, 'ru': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}, 'zh-CN': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}}, 'required': ['fr', 'es', 'it', 'ru', 'zh-CN']}}}}}
