2026-01-30 22:58:01,627 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-cab85ddc-bf36-4d96-b488-37da1e4b90df', 'json_data': {'input': "Translate the following Divento temporary exhibition content.\n\nRules (follow exactly):\n- Return ONLY a JSON object matching the provided schema.\n- Do not add citations, links, or URLs.\n- Avoid em/en dash characters (— or –); rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Keep all HTML tags intact in 'long' and return valid HTML.\n- Do NOT add extra blank lines/newlines.\n- For 'short': maximum 164 characters in the target language, keep natural phrasing.\n- For 'name': translate only what should be translated; keep proper nouns/titles as appropriate.\n- For zh-CN: translate ALL prose into Simplified Chinese; Latin script is allowed ONLY for proper nouns and official artwork/series titles.\n\nEnglish inputs:\n- name_en: Our Story with David Attenborough, Exhibition, Natural History Museum, London: 19 June 2025-31 August 2026\n- short_en: Study Earth’s deep-time turning points as David Attenborough narrates a wraparound film experience at the Natural History Museum in London.\nlong_en_html:\n<p>Across the galleries at The Natural History Museum, materials and techniques carry the argument without hype. The room stays dark and calm, then light and sound do the heavy lifting. David Attenborough’s narration keeps things plain-spoken, the same steady tone familiar from Planet Earth, Blue Planet II and A Life on Our Planet, but here it’s pinned to a single, continuous thread about how life changes, survives and sometimes vanishes. The approach feels closer to a clear lesson than a pep talk.</p><p>At the centre is a large-scale, wraparound projection that stitches crisp animation to real-world imagery in one flowing sequence. It moves from early oceans and the first simple life through bursts of diversity, mass extinctions and rapid adaptation, then lands firmly in the present. The highlight is the way the visuals shift scale without fuss, from microscopic processes to whole-planet systems, so evolution reads as pressure and response rather than a parade of creatures. Maps, timelines and simple diagrams keep the science legible.</p><p>Don’t miss the opening stretch, which compresses deep time into a few sharp ideas, with tectonic motion and changing atmospheres made easy to follow. Don’t miss the mid-section on extinction and recovery, where the soundtrack drops back and the images slow down, letting cause and effect sit in the mind. There’s a blunt clarity to the contrasts between stable climates and sudden shocks, and the film doesn’t dodge uncertainty, it names what scientists know and what remains debated.</p><p>The exhibition keeps the language grounded and avoids finger-pointing, even when it turns to human influence, land use and warming seas. Outside the screening space, the Museum’s wider context adds quiet weight: in Hintze Hall, the blue whale skeleton known as Hope hangs overhead, a reminder that real bodies sit behind the big ideas. That proximity makes the story feel less abstract, even when the focus stays on moving image rather than cases and labels.</p><p>A hidden gem is a small side section that unpacks the science behind the sequences with short text, diagrams and definitions, handy for anyone wanting key terms without a textbook tone. It’s also a good breather between the big scenes and the final run of images, where the narration shifts from what happened to what’s happening now, and the sound design keeps tension without turning it into theatre.</p>\n", 'max_output_tokens': 9000, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_translation_bundle', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'fr': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'n