2026-01-30 22:58:31,606 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-e0d0c9aa-ae7f-423b-b080-1e9dff97fbb2', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Van Eyck\n- Venue: The National Gallery\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Labels at The National Gallery keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Map\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Map a quiet route through early Netherlandish paint at the National Gallery in London, and catch details that flip the story.", "long": "<p>Labels at The National Gallery keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft. In London, UK, the Van Eyck rooms sit close to the heart of the collection and stay grounded in what paint can do on oak. There’s talk of trade and devotion, but it always comes back to touch, varnish, and the slow build-up of glazes.</p>\\n<p>A clear highlight is Jan van Eyck’s <i>The Arnolfini Portrait</i>, still weirdly intimate even in a busy gallery. The green gown holds its weight, the brass chandelier catches pinpoints of light, and the little dog looks stubbornly present. Two don’t-miss elements sit right in the picture: the convex mirror with its tiny reflected scene, and the Latin inscription, painted like a statement rather than a signature.</p>\\n<p>Another key stop is van Eyck’s <i>Portrait of a Man (Self Portrait?)</i>. The red chaperon reads as cloth and as design at the same time, and the direct gaze feels engineered, not accidental. Nearby context from peers such as Rogier van der Weyden and Petrus Christus helps the eye pick out what’s specifically van Eyck, the crisp transitions, the cool skin tones, the sense that oil paint can behave like enamel without turning flat.</p>\\n<p>The exhibition keeps materials in view without turning it into a lecture. Panels, ground layers, and microscopic details show how underdrawing steers a face before colour arrives, and how a final glaze can tighten shadows around an eyelid. Gold and textiles keep cropping up as problems to solve, not as decoration, with fur, velvet, and metal all treated as separate puzzles.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem sits in the margins, a small painted detail that’s easy to walk past because it looks like background. It’s the kind of quiet flourish, a bead of light on glass, a hairline crack in varnish, a thread caught by a highlight, that makes the whole thing feel less like a monument and more like a working object.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- long word count must be 350–400 (got 325)\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
