2026-01-30 22:59:25,681 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-ba74fa33-71b2-4760-bd93-87da6133033f', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: Van Eyck\n- Venue: The National Gallery\n- City: London\n- Country: UK\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –. If you want that pause, rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- 350 to 400 words. Target 380–395 words.\n- If you are under 350 words, add one more factual sentence to reach the minimum.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name or \'this exhibition\'.\n- Start the long description (immediately after <p>) with this exact sentence: Labels at The National Gallery keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft.\n- Avoid concluding sentences.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Start the short description with the exact first word \'Map\'.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\' and \'long\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Map a quiet route through early Netherlandish paint at The National Gallery in London, and catch details that flip the story.", "long": "<p>Labels at The National Gallery keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft. In London, the Van Eyck display stays anchored in what oil paint does on oak panel, and how that labour shows in every millimetre. It’s not a foggy tale of genius either, more a chain of choices: pigment, ground, underdrawing, then thin glazes that lock light into skin, cloth, metal, and glass. The room keeps scale honest, so tiny marks and big decisions sit side by side.</p>\\n<p>A clear highlight is Jan van Eyck’s <i>The Arnolfini Portrait</i>, still oddly intimate even with footfall and chatter nearby. The green gown holds real weight, the brass chandelier pricks out sharp points, and the little dog looks stubbornly present. Two don’t-miss elements sit right in the scene: the convex mirror, which catches a tiny reflected room, and the Latin inscription, painted like a public claim rather than a quiet signature. Pearls, oranges, and the carved bedpost land as hard, specific things, not symbols floating in space.</p>\\n<p>Another key stop is van Eyck’s <i>Portrait of a Man (Self Portrait?)</i>. The red chaperon reads as thick cloth and crisp design at the same time, and the stare feels engineered, not accidental. Close by, <i>Saint Francis Receiving the Stigmata</i> sharpens the sense of how van Eyck handles landscape, rock, and weathered skin with the same steady control. It’s the kind of painting that rewards calm looking, because every edge, from a bird’s wing to a friar’s robe, has a clear job.</p>\\n<p>The hang opens out into the wider field without losing focus. Rogier van der Weyden’s <i>The Magdalen Reading</i> offers a different kind of stillness, built from clean contours and tight surfaces. Petrus Christus pushes faces towards something more sculptural, and the architecture starts to feel measured rather than dreamlike. Taken together, the comparisons make van Eyck’s handling of light look less like magic and more like stubborn problem solving.</p>\\n<p>The wall text keeps materials in view without turning it into a lecture. Infrared and close-up images pull underdrawing into the open, showing a shifted mouth line, a tightened shadow under a chin, and the way a last glaze cools flesh without flattening it. A hidden gem sits inside the big painting’s details: the tiny Passion scenes around the mirror’s frame, each one a miniature with its own light and darkness.</p>"}\n\nFix these issues:\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['short', 'long']}}}}}
