2026-01-30 23:00:03,975 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-30ca4053-130c-4710-91dd-641045195795', 'json_data': {'input': "Translate the following Divento temporary exhibition content.\n\nRules (follow exactly):\n- Return ONLY a JSON object matching the provided schema.\n- Do not add citations, links, or URLs.\n- Avoid em/en dash characters (— or –); rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Keep all HTML tags intact in 'long' and return valid HTML.\n- Do NOT add extra blank lines/newlines.\n- For 'short': maximum 164 characters in the target language, keep natural phrasing.\n- For 'name': translate only what should be translated; keep proper nouns/titles as appropriate.\n- For zh-CN: translate ALL prose into Simplified Chinese; Latin script is allowed ONLY for proper nouns and official artwork/series titles.\n\nEnglish inputs:\n- name_en: Van Eyck, Exhibition, The National Gallery, London: 21 November 2026-11 April 2027\n- short_en: Map a quiet route through early Netherlandish paint at The National Gallery in London, and catch details that flip the story.\nlong_en_html:\n<p>Labels at The National Gallery keep attention on evidence, making the subject read through objects and craft. In London, the Van Eyck display stays anchored in what oil paint does on oak panel, and how that labour shows in every millimetre. It’s not a foggy tale of genius either, more a chain of choices: pigment, ground, underdrawing, then thin glazes that lock light into skin, cloth, metal, and glass. The room keeps scale honest, so tiny marks and big decisions sit side by side.</p><p>A clear highlight is Jan van Eyck’s <i>The Arnolfini Portrait</i>, still oddly intimate even with footfall and chatter nearby. The green gown holds real weight, the brass chandelier pricks out sharp points, and the little dog looks stubbornly present. Two don’t-miss elements sit right in the scene: the convex mirror, which catches a tiny reflected room, and the Latin inscription, painted like a public claim rather than a quiet signature. Pearls, oranges, and the carved bedpost land as hard, specific things, not symbols floating in space.</p><p>Another key stop is van Eyck’s <i>Portrait of a Man (Self Portrait?)</i>. The red chaperon reads as thick cloth and crisp design at the same time, and the stare feels engineered, not accidental. Close by, <i>Saint Francis Receiving the Stigmata</i> sharpens the sense of how van Eyck handles landscape, rock, and weathered skin with the same steady control. It’s the kind of painting that rewards calm looking, because every edge, from a bird’s wing to a friar’s robe, has a clear job.</p><p>The hang opens out into the wider field without losing focus. Rogier van der Weyden’s <i>The Magdalen Reading</i> offers a different kind of stillness, built from clean contours and tight surfaces. Petrus Christus pushes faces towards something more sculptural, and the architecture starts to feel measured rather than dreamlike. Taken together, the comparisons make van Eyck’s handling of light look less like magic and more like stubborn problem solving.</p><p>The wall text keeps materials in view without turning it into a lecture. Infrared and close-up images pull underdrawing into the open, showing a shifted mouth line, a tightened shadow under a chin, and the way a last glaze cools flesh without flattening it. A hidden gem sits inside the big painting’s details: the tiny Passion scenes around the mirror’s frame, each one a miniature with its own light and darkness.</p>\n", 'max_output_tokens': 9000, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_translation_bundle', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'fr': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}, 'es': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}, 'it': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}, 'ru': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}, 'zh-CN': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}}, 'required': ['fr', 'es', 'it', 'ru', 'zh-CN']}}}}}
